<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-426-394  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 426 394.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  August 1989 v2 n8 p211(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mike Falkner on databases. (Pro Tips)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Falkner, Mike.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data base management systemsInformation Storage and RetrievalTutorial.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Mike Falkner on DatabasesandM;There's more than one way to find information in dBASE.andP;  Knowing thedifferent search methods can save you a lot of time and frustration.andM;For a quick search, use the LIST command with a modifier.andP;  For example, LISTFOR LASTNAME=&quot;SMITH&quot; displays all records for the name SMITH.andP;  To be sure youcatch every instance of the name, including Smith or smith, use the followingcommand: LIST FOR UPPER (LASTNAME)=&quot;SMITH&quot;andM;To find both Smiths and Smyths, type LIST FOR LASTNAME=&quot;SM&quot; and you'll getrecords for any last name starting with sm.andP;  If you're looking for an unusualname, like Zyzynski, but you're not sure how it's spelled, enter: LIST FORAT(&quot;ski&quot;,LASTNAME)andless;andgt;0 and dBASE will display all records with ski anywhere inthe last name.andM;The LIST command is versatile, but it doesn't stop until it hits the end ofthe file or you hit the Escape key.andP;  If you substitute LOCATE for LIST, dBASEstops at the first record that matches the search.andP;  You can then type EDIT tochange the information, or type BROWSE or DISPLAY to look at records aroundthe record you found.andP;  To sve a few keystrokes, type: SET FILTER TOLASTNME=&quot;SMITH&quot; All commands you enter after FILTER, such as BROWSE and LIST,will automatically limit the display to records with SMITH.andM;For big files, however, sequential searches don't cut it.andP;  To speed thingsup, first index on your search field.andP;  Now you can use the FIND command.andO;Much like LOCATE, FIND will quickly locate the first occurrence of whatyou're looking for, but if the records are indexed, FIND finds it much morequickly.andP;  And if records are indexed, you can then use BROWSE or DISPLAY tolist the next few records that match your search without having to go throughthe whole file.andP;  FIND &quot;SM&quot; also works like LOCATE, finding the first matchwith only the first two letters, but it's a lot simpler to type because youdon't have to add all the details LOCATE requires.andP;  But FIND is casesensitive, so it won't find Sm and sm.andO;</TEXT></DOC>